    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-11-22T19:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-11-22T19:00:00-05:00" n="118"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d118">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">693.001/411a: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-11-22T19:00:00-05:00"
                            >November 22, 1938—7 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>397. At the press conference today the Secretary, in reply to a question relating
                    to the Japanese reply<note n="35a" xml:id="d118fn35a">
                        <ref target="frus1931-41v01#pg_797">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, Japan, 1931–1941, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p. 797</ref>.</note> to our note of October
                        6,<note n="36" xml:id="d118fn36">
                        <ref target="frus1931-41v01#pg_785">
                            <hi rend="italic">Ibid</hi>., p. 785</ref>.</note> stated that, of
                    course, it would be apparent to the correspondents that the Japanese reply is
                    not responsive to the position of this Government as set forth in our note of
                    October 6 and to the general position which this country has consistently taken,
                    throughout our history, with regard to American rights and interests not only in
                    relations with China but in relations with all countries. Beyond this, the
                    Secretary said, he preferred not to comment until the Department should have had
                    more time to study the substance and implications of the Japanese note.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
